public class JsElement
extends DOM2Core.Element.Prototype
implements EventTarget

An opaque class representing JavaScript client-side objects of the global JsClient.Element class.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
JavaScript:
Opaque types can be resolved but no class objects for them can be generated into the target codes. Re-compilers must exit with error on the operations of accessing that kind of class objects. The checkcast operation to the class literal of this class must be ignored and instanceof to it always true.

addEventListener

public final void addEventListener(java.lang.String type,
                                   JsFunction<?> listener,
                                   java.lang.Boolean useCapture)

Adds an event handler function to the set of event handlers for this element. This is a DOM-standard method supported by all modern browsers except IE.

This method adds the specified event listener function to the set of listeners registered on this node to handle events of the specified type. If useCapture is true, the listener is registered as a capturing event listener. If useCapture is false, it is registered as a normal event listener.

This method may be called multiple times to register multiple event handlers for the same type of event on the same node. Note, however, that the DOM Specification makes no guarantees about the order in which multiple event handlers are invoked.

If the same event listener function is registered twice on the same node with the same type and useCapture arguments, the second registration is simply ignored. If a new event listener is registered on this node while an event is being handled at this node, the new event listener is not invoked for that event.

When a node is duplicated with JsNode.cloneNode(Boolean) or JsDocument.importNode(JsNode, Boolean), the event listeners registered for the original node are not copied.

The same method is also defined by, and works analogously on, the JsDocument and JsWindow objects

Specified by:
addEventListener in interface EventTarget
Parameters:
type - The type of event for which the event listener is to be invoked.
listener - The event listener function that is invoked when an event of the specified type is dispatched to this node. When invoked, the listener function is passed an JsEvent object and is invoked as a method of the node on which it is registered.
useCapture - If true, the specified listener is to be invoked only during the capturing phase of event propagation. The more common value of false means that the listener is not invoked during the capturing phase but instead is invoked when this node is the actual event target or when the event bubbles up to this node from its original target.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
attachEvent(String, JsFunction), removeEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), JsDocument.addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), JsWindow.addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

removeEventListener

public final void removeEventListener(java.lang.String type,
                                      JsFunction<?> listener,
                                      java.lang.Boolean useCapture)

Removes an event handler function from the set of handlers for this element. This is a standard DOM method implemented by all modern browsers except IE.

This method removes the specified event listener function. The type and useCapture arguments must be the same as they are in the corresponding call to addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean). If no event listener is found that matches the specified arguments, this method does nothing.

Once an event listener function has been removed by this method, it will no longer be invoked for the specified type of event on this node. This is true even if the event listener is removed by another event listener registered for the same type of event on the same node.

The same method is also defined by, and works analogously on, the JsDocument and JsWindow objects

Specified by:
removeEventListener in interface EventTarget
Parameters:
type - The type of event for which the event listener is to be deleted.
listener - The event listener function that is to be removed.
useCapture - true if a capturing event listener is to be removed; false if a normal event listener is to be removed.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
detachEvent(String, JsFunction), addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), JsDocument.removeEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), JsWindow.removeEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean)

dispatchEvent

public final java.lang.Boolean dispatchEvent(JsEvent evt)

Dispatches a synthetic event to this element.

This method dispatches a synthetic event created with JsDocument.createEvent(String) and initialized with the initialization method defined by the JsEvent or one of its subclasses. The node on which this method is called becomes the target of the event, but the event first propagates down the document tree during the capturing phase, and then, if the JsEvent.bubbles property of the event is true, it bubbles up the document tree after being handled at the event target itself.

Parameters:
evt - The JsEvent object to be dispatched.
Returns:
false if the JsEvent.preventDefault() method of evt is called at any time during the propagation of the event, or true otherwise.
Throws:
java.lang.RuntimeException - JavaScript throws a JsError object if evt is not initialized, or if its JsEvent.type property is null or the empty string. See Js.err(Object) for JS Simulation.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
JsDocument.createEvent(String), JsEvent.initEvent(String, Boolean, Boolean), JsMouseEvent.initMouseEvent(String, Boolean, Boolean, JsWindow, Number, Number, Number, Number, Number, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean, Boolean, Number, JsElement), dispatchEvent(JsEvent)

attachEvent

public final void attachEvent(java.lang.String type,
                              JsFunction<?> listener)

Adds an event handler function to the set of handlers for this element. This is the IE-specific alternative to addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean).

This method is an IE-specific event registration method. It serves the same purpose as the standard addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean) method, which IE does not support, but is different from that function in several important ways:

  • Since the IE event model does not support event capturing, this method and detachEvent(String, JsFunction) expect only two arguments: the event type and the handler function.
  • The event handler names passed to the IE methods should include the "on" prefix.
  • Functions registered with this method are invoked with no JsEvent JsWindow.event property of JsWindow.window object.
  • Functions registered with this method are invoked as global functions, rather than as methods of the node on which the event occurred. That is, when an event handler registered with this method executes, the this keyword refers to JsWindow.window object, not to the event's target node.
  • This method allows the same event handler function to be registered more than once. When an event of the specified type occurs, the registered function is invoked as many times as it is registered.

The same method is also defined by, and works analogously on, the JsDocument and JsWindow objects

Specified by:
attachEvent in interface EventTarget
Parameters:
type - The type of event for which the event listener is to be invoked, with a leading "on" prefix.
listener - The event listener function that is invoked when an event of the specified type is dispatched to this node. This function is not passed any JsWindow.event property of the JsWindow object.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
addEventListener(String, JsFunction, Boolean), detachEvent(String, JsFunction), JsDocument.attachEvent(String, JsFunction), JsWindow.attachEvent(String, JsFunction)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

getAttribute

public final java.lang.String getAttribute(java.lang.String name)

Returns the value of a named attribute as a string.

This method returns the value of a named attribute of an element. Note that the JsHTMLElement objects have JavaScript properties that match each of the standard HTML attributes, so you need to use this method with HTML documents only if you are querying the value of nonstandard attributes.

In XML documents, attribute values are not available directly as element properties and must be looked up by calling this method. For XML documents that use name spaces, use getAttributeNS(String, String).

Parameters:
name - The name of the attribute whose value is to be returned.
Returns:
The value of the named attribute as a string. If the attribute is not defined, this method is supposed to return an empty string. Some implementations return null in this case, however.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
getAttribute(StringLike), getAttributeNS(String, String)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

This method is useful only with XML documents that use name spaces and works just like the getAttribute(String) method, except that the attribute is specified by a combination of name space URI and local name within that name space.

getElementsByTagName

public final JsNodeList<? extends JsElement> getElementsByTagName(java.lang.String name)

Returns an array, technically a JsNodeList object, of all JsElement nodes in the current document that have the specified tag name by traversing all descendants of this element. The JsElement nodes appear in the returned array in the same order in which they appear in the document source.

Note that the JsDocument.getElementsByTagName(String) method works just like this one but that traverses the entire document, rather than just the descendants of a single element. Do not confuse this method with JsHTMLDocument.getElementsByName(String), which searches for elements based on the value of their name attributes rather than by their tag names.

Parameters:
name - The tag name of the desired elements, or the value "*" to specify that all descendant elements should be returned, regardless of their tag names.
Returns:
An read-only array, technically a JsNodeList object, of JsElement nodes that are descendants of this element and have the specified tag name.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
getElementsByTagName(StringLike), JsDocument.getElementsByTagName(String), JsDocument.getElementById(String), JsHTMLDocument.getElementsByName(String)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

getElementsByTagNameNS

public final JsNodeList<? extends JsElement> getElementsByTagNameNS(java.lang.String namespaceURI,
                                                                    java.lang.String localName)

Returns an array of all JsElement nodes in the current document that have the specified tag name and name-space by traversing all descendants of this element.

This method works like getElementsByTagName(String), except that the tag name of the desired elements is specified as a combination of a name space URI and a local name defined within that name space. This method is useful only with XML documents that use name spaces.

Parameters:
namespaceURI - The URI that uniquely identifies the name space of the desired elements.

removeAttribute

public final void removeAttribute(java.lang.String name)

Removes the named attribute from this element.

This method deletes a named attribute from this element. If the named attribute has a default value specified by the document type, subsequent calls to this method return that default value. Attempts to remove nonexistent attributes or attributes that are not specified but have a default value are silently ignored.

Parameters:
name - The name of the desired attribute.
Throws:

removeAttributeNode

public final JsAttr removeAttributeNode(JsAttr attr)

Removes the specified JsAttr node from the list of attributes for this element.

This method removes and returns a JsAttr node from the set of attributes of an element. If the removed attribute has a default value specified by the DTD, a new JsAttr node is added representing this default value. It is often simpler to use removeAttribute(String) instead of this method.

setAttribute

public final void setAttribute(java.lang.String name,
                               java.lang.Object value)

Sets or adds the named attribute to the specified string value.

This method sets the specified attribute to the specified value. If no attribute by that name already exists, a new one is created.

Note that JsHTMLElement objects of an HTML document define JavaScript properties that correspond to all standard HTML attributes. Thus, you need to use this method only if you want to set a nonstandard attribute.

Parameters:
name - The name of the attribute to be created or modified.
value - The string value of the attribute.
Throws:
java.lang.RuntimeException - JavaScript throws a JsDOMException object with the JsDOMException.code property of the value JsDOMException.NO_MODIFICATION_ALLOWED_ERR if this element is read-only and does not allow its attributes to be removed or the value JsDOMException.INVALID_CHARACTER_ERR if the name argument contains a character that is not allowed in HTML or XML attribute names. See Js.err(Object) for JS Simulation.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
getAttribute(String), removeAttribute(String), setAttributeNode(JsAttr)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.

setAttributeNode

public final JsAttr setAttributeNode(JsAttr attr)

Sets or adds the specified JsAttr node to the list of attributes for this element.

If an attribute with the same name already exists for this element, attr replaces that attribute, and the replaced JsAttr node is returned. If no such attribute already exists, this method defines a new attribute for the element.

It is usually easier to use setAttribute(String, Object) instead of this method.

Parameters:
attr - The JsAttr node that represents the attribute to be added or whose value is to be modified.
Returns:
The JsAttr node that was replaced by attr, or null if no attribute was replaced.
Throws:
java.lang.RuntimeException - JavaScript throws a JsDOMException object with the JsDOMException.code property of the value JsDOMException.NO_MODIFICATION_ALLOWED_ERR if this element is read-only and does not allow its attributes to be removed, the value JsDOMException.INUSE_ATTRIBUTE_ERR if attr is already a member of the attribute set of some other JsElement node, or the value JsDOMException.WRONG_DOCUMENT_ERR if attr has a different JsNode.ownerDocument property than the JsElement node on which it is being set. See Js.err(Object) for JS Simulation.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
getAttribute(StringLike)
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert the instance invocation of this method directly into a JavaScript invocation on its current object instance without changing the method name, but expanding variable arguments, if any, into comma-separated values.
